smart pointers
  wrappers around pointers to avoid manual memory management
  if we do manual memory management, errors can lead to
    > memory leaks
    > double frees
    > use after free
    > dangling pointers
      
  
  `#include <memory>` header
  
  ```normal example
  Board* b = new Board;
  delete b;
  ```
  ```with smart pointer
  std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();
  ```

  smart pointers use RAII (Resource Aquistion Is Initialization)
    basically memory is freed when object goes out of scope
    this is what stack objects do by default

  3 main types of smart pointers
    unique_ptr   ->  single owner
    shared_ptr   ->  multiple owners
    weak_ptr     ->  non owning observer

  unique_ptr
    exclusive ownership

    only one pointer owns the object
    ```std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();```
    use like a normal pointer
    when out of scope, it gets deleted automatically
    
    ```
      {
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();
      } // deleted
    ```

    cannot copy 
      ```
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_unique<Board>();
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b2 = b1; // NOT POSSIBLE
      ```

    can move
      ```
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_unique<Board>();
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b2 = std::move(b1); 
        // b2 now owns the object
        // b1 becomes null
      ```
  shared pointer
    multiple pointers own the same object
    object is deleted when total references become 0

    ```
    {
      std::shared_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_shared<Board>();
      {
        std::shared_ptr<Board> b2 = b1;
      } // b2 is destroyed, count down to 1
    } // count is 0, object is destroyed

  problem with shared pointers
    suppose we have two shared pointers A and B
    and we set their property so that
      A->b = B  
      B->a = A
    now, they both depend on each other, so they will not be freed when they go out of scope
    because the count doesn't go to 0

    for this there exists weak_ptr
  
  weak_ptr
    doesn't own objects
    
    `weak_ptr<A> a = sharedPtr;` 
    doesnt increase the count

    you cannot directly access the weak pointer since the shared pointer might have been destroyed
    so you have to lock it

    ```
    // wp -> weak pointer
    wp->a; // NOT POSSIBLE

    if (shared_ptr<TypeHere> sp = wp.lock()) {
      std::cout << sp->a;
    }
    ```
    lock()
      returns a shared pointer, if the object is alive
      nullptr if destroyed

    checking expiration
      `wp.expired() // false or true, prefer lock()`

constexpr
  allows you to move computation from runtime to compile time, if the values are known at compile time

  constexpr variables
    `constexpr int x = 1;`
    compiler guarantees value known at compile time 
    stored in read only memory
    can be used in constexpr expressions

  example
    ```
      constexpr int SIZE = 64;
      int board[SIZE]; // compile time, because SIZE is constexpr
    ```

  constexpr functions 
    functions that CAN run at compile time (i.e runtime or compile time based on context)
    ```
        constexpr int square(int x) {
          return x * x;
        }
      constexpr int y = square(5); // compile time
    ```

    this function can also be run time
    ```
      int n;
      std::cin >> n;
      
      int y = square(n); // run time
    ```

    there are many rules for a constexpr function to be compile time evaluable
    some are
      > return literal types
      > simple statements
      > no dynamic allocation
      > no i/o
      > no virtual calls (runtime polymorphism)
      > modern cpp allows loops

  difference between constexpr and const variables
    const -> cannot change value and may or may not be known at compile time
    constexpr -> cannot change value and has to be known at compile time

  constexpr objects
    you can create compile time objects
    ex
      ``` 
        struct Point {
          int x, y;

          constexpr Point(int a, int b) : x(a), y(b) {}
        };
        
        constexpr Point p(3, 2); // compile time
      ```

    constexpr methods

    ```
      struct Square {
        int side;

        constexpr int area() const { // const objects can only all const methods
          return side * side;
        }
      };

      constexpr Square s{5};
      constexpr int a = s.area();
    ```
  
